</span><hr size=1>      Chloe looked up at the apartment’s fire escape, tears running down her face.  She put her hand on the cold steel of the ladder and began climbing up it.  Sobbing as she went, after several minutes she reached the top.  She pulled her self over, and gazed across the city into the orange sunset.  She looked and saw a mother in a lawn chair, two small children playing jacks at her feet.  Instantly, a flood of memories came gushing into her head.  She was sent back to a happier times, a time where she too played in front of her mother with her little brother.  She remembered the day it all happened, the sick crack of her brother’s legs as he fell.  She didn't mean to do what she did; it was... it was...she stopped herself.   But what could she have done to prevent it? She was so angry, angry at her mother for never being there.  She was angry at her responsibility; it seemed, to solve all the family's problems.  She needed to be a child, she was sick of it.  Sick of being the adult. She leaned over the top of the building and swallowed.  She new what she had to do.<br>
     But then she heard the children laughing.  She looked down and saw the three hug.  She knew she couldn't do what she intended.  She gazed out over the orange sky, and felt that somewhere out there was a person who, even though had caused her so much pain, loved her with all her heart.  A person who blamed themselves for everything Chloe had put her self through.  Chloe sighed and turned away, a sick smile on her face.  She trembled and fell to her knees, sobbing once more.<br>
